notesStmt.note: This Book of Hours was created ca. 1470 in Bruges by a follower of Willem Vrelant. The manuscript contains eleven extant large miniatures and one small miniature, which are representative of the standard style established by Willem Vrelant. Collects following the Office of the Dead are for a mother, father, deceased male, and a female suppliant, which offers insight into the book's use.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Latin.

msItem.title: Calendar
msItem.rubric: Januarius habet dies. xxxi. luna. xxx.
msItem.note: Calendar less than half full; graded in red and black; contents suggest Bruges; saints of note include Bathildis (Jan. 31), Basil (Jun. 14), Eligius (Jun. 25), Anne (Jul. 24, "matris marie"), Agapitus (Aug. 17, usually Aug. 18), Aegydius (Sept. 1), Remigius and Bavo (Oct. 1), Donatian (Oct. 14), Theodore (Nov. 10)

msItem.title: Hours of the Holy Spirit
msItem.rubric: Hore de sancto spiritu ad matutinas
msItem.note: Folio from vespers in Office of the Dead included after fol. 13

msItem.title: Mass of the Virgin, Gospel sequences, and prayers
msItem.incipit: ... dei et vos orare pro me peccatore
msItem.note: Mass of the Virgin begins imperfectly; fols. 16r-20v: Mass of the Virgin; fols. 20v-25v: Gospel Sequence; fols. 25v-31v: Two prayers to the Virgin; fols. 25v-29v: Obsecro te; fols. 29v-31v: O intemerata

msItem.title: Hours of the Virgin
msItem.note: Headings of canonical hours start at fol. 42r

msItem.title: Litany, petitions, and collects
msItem.note: Composite, incomplete list of confessors and lacking virgins after fol. 89v; fols. 87v-89v: litany, including sixteen apostles from Peter to Mark; nineteen martyrs, including Lupus, Amantius, Donatus and Blasius; nine doctores, including seven popes: Remegius and Vedastus; six remaining confessors, including Leonard, Bernard, Francis, Eligius, Aegydius and Dominic; fols. 90r-92v: petitions; 92v-94v: nine collects

msItem.title: Office of the Dead
msItem.incipit: ...reges terre quia audierunt omnia verba oris tue
msItem.note: Short version; Office of the Dead vespers begins imperfectly; image with opening text missing, and following the folio from Vespers misbound after fol. 13r; fols. 96v-97r: three collects after Vespers, for mother, father and deceased male signified by "N" for the name

support.p: Lightweight, fairly well prepared and selected; flyleaves modern woven paper

supportDesc.foliation: Modern pencil foliation, upper right corners rectos

collation.p: Quire 1: 6 (fols. 1-6); Quire 2: 8, with eighth folio misbound, moved from quite 13 (fols. 7-15); Quire 3: 8, with first folio removed (fols. 16-22); Quires 4-9: 8 (fols. 23-70); Quire 10: 6 (fols. 71-76); Quire 11: 8 (fols. 77-84); Quire 12: 8, with sixth folio cancelled (fols. 85-91); Quire 13: 8, with fourth folio removed, fifth folio misbound in quire 2 (fols. 92-97); Quire 13: 10 (fols. 98-107) None None In quire 2 the 8th folio is misbound after fol. 13, and would have originally been the 5th folio in quire 13

layoutDesc.layout: Ruled in light red ink; layout does not apply to calender; written area 6.2 x 11.4 cm; 4 columns of 17 lines

decoDesc.decoNote: Large miniature with rubric and incipit missing after fol. 94

Eleven extant large miniatures, one extant small miniature (two missing); foliate borders around miniatures only; large decorated initials at major text openings accompanying miniatures (4 lines); small decorated initials at secondary text divisions and at "K L" in calendar (2 lines); small flourished initials in versals in alternating blue and gold (1 line); foliate line fillers in alternating red and blue; rubrics in red; text in dark brown ink

binding.p: Red velvet, early twentieth century, Belgium (?); parchment bands resewn, rounded spine; endbands include edge-bead around cord; copper clasp on center of upper board fore-edge; page edges are yellow-tinted

history.provenance: Created c. 1470 in Bruges by follower of Willem Vrelant; prayers suggest both male and female suppliants, fols. 96v-97v
history.acquisition: Walters Art Museum, 1931, by Henry Walters' bequest
